          <avActivityHighlights>Slab avalanches are the main danger. Moist and wet avalanches are possible in the second half of the day.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of the strong northwesterly wind, fresh snow drift accumulations formed during the last few days. &lt;br/&gt; In particular intermediate and high altitudes as well as in places that are protected from the wind: Soft wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant in areas close to the tree line. The wind slabs are clearly recognisable. &lt;br/&gt; In particular steep sunny slopes and base of rock walls: Medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large dry and moist avalanches are possible as a consequence of warming.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Over a wide area 15 to 20 cm of snow fell yesterday in all altitude zones. The strong wind has transported the fresh and old snow. &lt;br/&gt; In particular in the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. Shady slopes: The snowpack is dry and has a loosely bonded surface. &lt;br/&gt; Sunny slopes: The solar radiation will give rise as the day progresses to increasing moistening of the snowpack.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
